A closure in JavaScript is a feature where an inner functions have access to the scope of their outer (enclosing) function, even after the outer function has finished executing.
Here is a 3-line example:
```javascript
function outerFunction(x) {
  return function innerFunction() {
    return x + 1; // innerFunction has access to x from outerFunction's scope
  };
}
}
const closure = outerFunction(5);
console.log(closure()); // Output: 10
```
